'''Jude Victor William Bellingham''' (born 29 June 2003) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{Spanish football updater|Real Madrid}} club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]]. Known for his exceptional work rate, playmaking ability, interceptions and fast dribbling, he is widely regarded as one of the best players in the world.<ref name="2024 Ballon d'Or" /><ref name="FIFA The Best 2024" />

Bellingham joined [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] as an under-8, became the club's youngest [[First team (association football)|first-team]] player when he made his senior debut in August 2019, at the age of {{age in years and days|2003|6|29|2019|8|6}}, and played regularly during the [[2019–20 Birmingham City F.C. season|2019–20 season]]. He joined [[Borussia Dortmund]] in July 2020, and in his first appearance became the club's youngest goal-scorer. Over three seasons with the club he made 132 appearances and won the [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal]]; his performances in the [[2022–23 Bundesliga|2022–23 season]] helped Dortmund finish as runners-up and earned him the [[2022–23 Bundesliga#Annual awards|Bundesliga Player of the Season]] award. Later that year he won both major awards for male footballers aged under 21: the European [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]] and the worldwide [[Kopa Trophy]].<ref name="2023 GoldenBoy" /><ref name="2023Kopa" />

He then signed for Real Madrid for a fee of €103&nbsp;million. In his first season, Bellingham was the club's top league scorer, helped them win [[2023–24 La Liga|the league title]] and the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], and was voted [[La Liga Awards#Player of the season|La Liga Player of the Season]].<ref name="Liga PotS" /> He was included in the [[FIFPRO World 11]] for three consecutive years (2023, 2024, 2025) and finished third in the [[Ballon d'Or]] and [[FIFA The Best]] in 2024.

Bellingham represented England at under-15, [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels. He made his first appearance for the senior team in November 2020, and was part of the squads for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024]] as well as the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

==Early life and education==
Jude Victor William Bellingham<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/image/201920/general-news/efl-squad-numbering-06.09.2019.pdf |title=Notification of shirt numbers: Birmingham City |publisher=English Football League |page=4 |access-date=15 October 2019 |archive-date=26 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126223301/https://www.efl.com/siteassets/image/201920/general-news/efl-squad-numbering-06.09.2019.pdf}}</ref> was born on 29 June 2003<ref name="Soccerway"/> in [[Stourbridge]], in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Dudley]], West Midlands,<ref name="Youngest"/> the eldest son of Denise and [[Mark Bellingham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bvb.de/eng/News/Overview/Jude-Bellingham-Young.-Good.-And-really-cool |title=Jude Bellingham: Young. Good. And really cool. |first=Sven |last=Goldmann |publisher=Borussia Dortmund |date=9 October 2020 |access-date=13 November 2020 |archive-date=27 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227033301/https://www.bvb.de/eng/News/Overview/Jude-Bellingham-Young.-Good.-And-really-cool |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="EFL YP Nov 19"/> He is of Irish descent through his father, and Kenyan descent through his mother.<ref name="auto">{{cite web |url=https://extra.ie/2022/11/20/sport/soccernews/irish-qualified-2022-world-cup |title=Every Irish-qualified football player at the 2022 World Cup |first=Rob |last=O'Halloran |website=Extra.ie |date=20 November 2022 |access-date=8 January 2023 |archive-date=20 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221120071305/https://extra.ie/2022/11/20/sport/soccernews/irish-qualified-2022-world-cup |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/bellingham-en-bilbao-38038466|title=Bellingham en Bilbao|date=4 August 2025|website=OneFootball}}</ref> His father Mark was, until 2022, a sergeant in the [[West Midlands Police]], and a prolific goalscorer in [[non-League football]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/latest-news/step-five-and-below/17046/700-up-legendary-striker-mark-bellingham-on-reaching-the-amazing-milestone/ |title=700-up! Legendary striker Mark Bellingham on reaching the amazing milestone |first=Steven |last=Coney |newspaper=The Non-League Paper |date=22 September 2016 |access-date=29 March 2019 |archive-date=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807081646/https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/latest-news/step-five-and-below/17046/700-up-legendary-striker-mark-bellingham-on-reaching-the-amazing-milestone/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="EFL YP Nov 19"/><ref>{{cite tweet |author=Mark Bellingham |user=Bello1966 |number=1591982107542552576 |title=As of midnight I became a civilian after 24+ years service. Cops ain't perfect but they're tryng [sic] their best under difficult circumstances. If we can show kindness to eachother [sic], we have a chance |date=14 November 2022 |access-date=8 January 2023}}</ref> Bellingham's younger brother, [[Jobe Bellingham|Jobe]], is also a footballer.<ref name="Guardian Fisher"/> Bellingham was [[Private schools in the United Kingdom|privately educated]] at Priory School in [[Edgbaston]], [[Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/black-country/inside-16k-year-edgbaston-school-25676196|title=Inside the £16K-a-year Edgbaston school attended by World Cup hero Jude Bellingham|first=Nathan|last=Clarke|year=2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221206094934/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/black-country/inside-16k-year-edgbaston-school-25676196|archive-date=6 December 2022|website=birminghammail.co.uk|publisher=[[Birmingham Mail]]}}</ref><ref name="Sky Bate"/> He grew up idolising [[Zinedine Zidane]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akhilomen |first=Austin |date=2 November 2023 |title=Zidane is my idol – Bellingham |url=https://www.completesports.com/zidane-is-my-idol-bellingham/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=6 May 2024 |newspaper=[[Complete Sports]]|language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231106220651/https://www.completesports.com/zidane-is-my-idol-bellingham/ |archive-date=6 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bellingham graduated from [[Loughborough College]] with a [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTEC]] level 3 certificate in sport in 2021.<ref name=lough>{{cite web|title=Loughborough College Legend Jude Bellingham Continues on Record-Breaking Path|author=Anon|year=2023|website=loucoll.ac.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702194104/https://www.loucoll.ac.uk/news/loughborough-college-legend-jude-bellingham-continues-on-record-breaking-path|archive-date=2 July 2023 |publisher=[[Loughborough College]]|url=https://www.loucoll.ac.uk/news/loughborough-college-legend-jude-bellingham-continues-on-record-breaking-path}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Birmingham City===
Bellingham joined [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] as an under-8,<ref name="Youngest"/> after playing for [[Stourbridge F.C.|Stourbridge Juniors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/england/mens-senior-team/squad/jude-bellingham |title=Jude Bellingham |publisher=The Football Association |access-date=6 June 2024 |archive-date=15 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315031215/https://www.englandfootball.com/england/mens-senior-team/squad/jude-bellingham |url-status=live}}</ref> He played for their under-18 team at 14,<ref name="Guardian Fisher"/> and made his debut for their under-23 team at the age of 15, on 15 October 2018 away to [[Nottingham Forest]]'s U23s. Entering the game after an hour, he scored the only goal in the 87th minute "sliding in to force the ball over the goal line after pressure by Kyle McFarlane on the keeper diverted the ball into his path."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/archive/report-nottingham-forest-under-23s-0-blues-under-23s-1 |title=Report: Nottingham Forest Under-23s 0 Blues Under-23s 1 |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=15 October 2018 |access-date=3 September 2022 |archive-date=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807081654/https://www.bcfc.com/news/articles/2018/report-nottingham-forest-under-23s-0-blues-under-23s-1/ |url-status=live}}</ref> By March 2019, he had three goals from ten development squad appearances,<ref name="19th Man" /> had featured in ''[[FourFourTwo]]''{{'s}} list of the "50 most exciting teenagers in English football",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/50-most-exciting-teenagers-english-football |title=The 50 most exciting teenagers in English football |website=FourFourTwo |date=20 February 2019 |access-date=30 March 2019 |archive-date=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406072954/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/50-most-exciting-teenagers-english-football |url-status=live}}</ref> and was mentioned as of interest to major European clubs.<ref name="19th Man"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/10/englands-youth-auditioning-star-roles-bundesliga-clubs-increasingly/ |title=While Bundesliga clubs sense opportunity, England's youth face difficult choice over whether to stick or twist |first=Sam |last=Wallace |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=10 March 2019 |access-date=29 March 2019 |archive-date=10 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190310210757/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/10/englands-youth-auditioning-star-roles-bundesliga-clubs-increasingly/ |url-status=live}}</ref> He was gradually introduced to the [[First team (association football)|first-team]] environment while still a schoolboy: increasingly training with the seniors, he accompanied them on matchday to observe,<ref name="Guardian Fisher">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/football-league-blog/2020/feb/20/jude-bellingham-on-the-radar-of-footballs-powerhouses-birmingham-city-midfielder-aged-16 |title=Why Jude Bellingham is already on the radar of football's powerhouses |first=Ben |last=Fisher |website=The Guardian |location=London |date=20 February 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-date=25 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225235153/https://www.theguardian.com/football/football-league-blog/2020/feb/20/jude-bellingham-on-the-radar-of-footballs-powerhouses-birmingham-city-midfielder-aged-16 |url-status=live}}</ref> and travelled as the "19th man" for a [[EFL Championship|Championship]] match in March.<ref name="19th Man">{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-jude-bellingham-bcfc-16051290 |title=Who is Jude Bellingham? A quick introduction to Birmingham City's teenage wonder boy |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=30 March 2019 |access-date=30 March 2019 |archive-date=30 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330152402/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-jude-bellingham-bcfc-16051290 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Bellingham took up a two-year scholarship with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] to begin in July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/birmingham-city-coach-makes-jude-16620554 |title=Birmingham City coach makes this Jude Bellingham transfer admission |first=Bradley |last=Rice |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=20 July 2019 |access-date=2 August 2019 |archive-date=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807081646/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/birmingham-city-coach-makes-jude-16620554 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was part of the first-team training camp in Portugal,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/revealed-birmingham-city-confirm-26-16544471 |title=Birmingham City confirm 26-man squad for Portugal tour |first=Alex |last=Dicken |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=2 August 2019 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030154/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/revealed-birmingham-city-confirm-26-16544471 |url-status=live}}</ref> played and scored in [[pre-season friendlies]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/archive/report-blues-6-swindon-town-1 |title=Report: Blues 6 Swindon Town 1 |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=19 July 2019 |access-date=3 September 2022 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719151621/https://www.bcfc.com/news/articles/2019/report-blues-6-swindon-town-1/ |url-status=live}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-pep-16619550 |title=Birmingham City player ratings as Pep Clotet's men win again in pre-season |first=Joseph |last=Chapman |website=Birmingham Live |date=20 July 2019 |access-date=20 July 2019 |archive-date=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720144917/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-pep-16619550 |url-status=live}}</ref> and was given [[Squad number (association football)|squad number]] 22 for the [[2019–20 Birmingham City F.C. season|2019–20 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/archive/blues-2019-20-squad-numbers |title=Blues 2019/20 squad numbers |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=2 August 2019 |access-date=2 September 2022 |archive-date=2 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802131301/https://www.bcfc.com/news/articles/2019/blues-201920-squad-numbers/ |url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 August, when he started the [[2019–20 EFL Cup#First round|EFL Cup first round]] visit to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], Bellingham became the youngest first-team player in Birmingham City's history. At {{age in years and days|2003|6|29|2019|8|6}}, he lowered the record set by [[Trevor Francis]] in 1970 by 101 days.<ref name="Youngest">{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/archive/bellingham-creates-blues-history |title=Bellingham creates Blues history |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=6 August 2019 |access-date=3 September 2022 |archive-date=30 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200430082546/https://www.bcfc.com/news/articles/2019/bellingham-creates-blues-history/ |url-status=live}}</ref> He played for 80 minutes in the 3–0 defeat, and was the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]''{{'s}} [[man of the match]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-jude-16711571 |title=Birmingham City player ratings: Jude Bellingham shines bright despite defeat |first=Joseph |last=Chapman |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=6 August 2019 |access-date=6 August 2019 |archive-date=6 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806224904/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-jude-16711571 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his first [[English Football League|Football League]] appearance 19 days later, as a second-half [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 3–0 defeat away to [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]],<ref name=sb1920 /> and his home debut on 31 August against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]. Replacing the injured [[Jefferson Montero]] after half an hour, Bellingham scored the winner{{snd}}albeit via a generous deflection{{snd}}as Birmingham came back from 1–0 down to beat Stoke 2–1, and thus became their youngest goalscorer, aged {{age in years and days|2003|6|29|2019|8|31}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/birmham-vs-stoke/report/409408 |title=Birmingham 2–1 Stoke: Blues comeback heaps more pressure on Nathan Jones |website=Sky Sports |date=31 August 2019 |access-date=1 September 2019 |archive-date=1 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901112344/https://www.skysports.com/football/birmham-vs-stoke/report/409408 |url-status=live}}</ref> He started the next match, away to [[Charlton Athletic]] two weeks later, and scored the only goal from [[Kerim Mrabti]]'s cutback.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617723 |title=Charlton Athletic 0–1 Birmingham City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2019 |access-date=15 September 2019 |archive-date=14 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914170249/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617723 |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Jude Bellingham Birmingham 2019.jpg|thumb|upright|Bellingham with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 2019]]

Bellingham continued as a permanent fixture in the matchday squad, sometimes as a substitute but mainly in the starting eleven.<ref name="Sky Bate">{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/11914861/jude-bellingham-to-manchester-united-birmingham-teenager-is-a-special-talent |title=Jude Bellingham to Manchester United? Birmingham teenager is a special talent |first=Adam |last=Bate |website=Sky Sports |date=25 January 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304093656/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/11914861/jude-bellingham-to-manchester-united-birmingham-teenager-is-a-special-talent |url-status=live}}</ref> He was eased into the team [[midfielder#Winger|on the left wing]], moved into [[central midfield]] "where he could gain more confidence", and then used "in a more advanced role" once the staff were sure he could cope with the responsibility.<ref name="Sky Bate"/> He was [[EFL Young Player of the Month]] for November 2019.<ref name="EFL YP Nov 19"/> According to head coach [[Pep Clotet]], Bellingham himself "feels more comfortable in midfield, and more comfortable when he can get closer to the opposition box."<ref name="Times Robertson">{{cite news |url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A612379131/STND?u=wikipedia&sid=bookmark-STND&xid=de1a8bac |title='No ceiling' on how far Jude Bellingham, 16, can go |first=Gregor |last=Robertson |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=27 January 2020 |page=14 |access-date=15 September 2021 |via=Gale OneFile: News |url-access=subscription |archive-date=10 October 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241010001623/https://go.gale.com/ps/i.do?p=STND&u=wikipedia&id=GALE%7CA612379131&v=2.1&it=r&sid=bookmark-STND&asid=de1a8bac |url-status=live }}</ref>

Bellingham was linked with moves to numerous major clubs in January 2020;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/1234610/Chelsea-transfer-news-Jude-Bellingham-Man-Utd-doubt-latest-rumours |title=Chelsea submit bid for Man Utd target as player's father has doubts over Old Trafford move |first=Lewis |last=Winter |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030155/https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/1234610/Chelsea-transfer-news-Jude-Bellingham-Man-Utd-doubt-latest-rumours |url-status=live}}</ref> on [[transfer window|deadline day]], Birmingham were reported to have turned down a £20&nbsp;million bid from [[Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/birmingham-city-mufc-transfers-deadline-17666732 |title=Birmingham City transfer deadline day: Blues reject huge Manchester United bid – reports |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=31 January 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226154819/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/birmingham-city-mufc-transfers-deadline-17666732 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bellingham continued as a first-team regular, and by the time the season was suspended because of the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]], he had made 32 league appearances. He remained an integral part of the team once the season resumed [[behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]],<ref name=sb1920/> and set up a late equaliser for [[Lukas Jutkiewicz]] against Charlton Athletic that made Birmingham's league position less precarious with two matches still to play.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53330122 |title=Birmingham City 1–1 Charlton Athletic |first=Andrew |last=Aloia |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 July 2020 |access-date=16 July 2020 |archive-date=15 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200715110746/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53330122 |url-status=live}}</ref> He finished the season with four goals from 44 appearances in all competitions, 41 in the league, as Birmingham avoided relegation despite losing the last match of the season.<ref name=sb1920 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/birmham-vs-derby/report/409888 |title=Birmingham 1–3 Derby: Blues secure Championship status despite defeat |website=Sky Sports |date=22 July 2020 |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=24 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200724012224/https://www.skysports.com/football/birmham-vs-derby/report/409888 |url-status=live}}</ref> In appreciation of what Bellingham achieved in such a short time with the first team, the club announced that they would retire his number 22 shirt, "to remember one of our own and to inspire others."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/birmingham-city-retire-jude-bellingham-number-22-shirt-borussia-dortmund-transfer-a9634516.html |title=Jude Bellingham's number 22 shirt retired by Birmingham City after Borussia Dortmund transfer |first=Jack |last=de Menezes |newspaper=The Independent |date=23 July 2020 |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=23 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200723153650/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/birmingham-city-retire-jude-bellingham-number-22-shirt-borussia-dortmund-transfer-a9634516.html |url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[EFL Awards]], he was named both [[Football League Apprentice of the Year#Championship|Championship Apprentice of the Year]] and EFL Young Player of the Season.<ref name=EFLAwards/>

===Borussia Dortmund===
It was clear that Bellingham would leave Birmingham, and it was reported that he and his father had visited several major clubs, of which Manchester United and [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia Dortmund]] were the favourites.<ref name="Signs Dortmund">{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11899/12029767/jude-bellingham-signs-for-borussia-dortmund-from-birmingham |title=Jude Bellingham signs for Borussia Dortmund from Birmingham |website=Sky Sports |date=20 July 2020 |access-date=20 July 2020 |archive-date=20 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200720121831/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11899/12029767/jude-bellingham-signs-for-borussia-dortmund-from-birmingham |url-status=live}}</ref> Impressed by Dortmund's record of including young players as regulars in the first team, as evidenced by the likes of [[Jadon Sancho]], Bellingham reportedly settled on the club as his destination of choice. He flew to Germany for a [[Physical examination|medical]], and the transfer was confirmed on 20 July 2020. Bellingham was to join after Birmingham's last match of the season.<ref name="Signs Dortmund"/> The undisclosed fee was understood by [[Sky Sports]] to be an initial £25&nbsp;million{{snd}}making him the most expensive 17-year-old in history{{snd}}plus "several million more" dependent on performance-related criteria.<ref name="Signs Dortmund"/>

====2020–2021: Transfer and record-breaking achievements====
Bellingham made his debut on 14 September 2020, starting the first match of the [[2020–21 Borussia Dortmund season|2020–21 season]] against third-tier [[MSV Duisburg]] in the [[DFB-Pokal]], aged 17 years, 77 days. After half an hour, he scored the second goal in a 5–0 win, becoming the club's youngest goalscorer in the DFB-Pokal, taking six days off [[Giovanni Reyna]]'s record, as well as their youngest scorer in any competitive match, breaking [[Nuri Şahin]]'s record by five days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bvb.de/eng/News/Overview/The-youngest-goalscorer-and-the-fastest-goal-by-a-substitute |title=The youngest goalscorer and the fastest goal by a substitute |publisher=Borussia Dortmund |date=14 September 2020 |access-date=15 September 2020 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030207/https://www.bvb.de/eng/News/Overview/The-youngest-goalscorer-and-the-fastest-goal-by-a-substitute |url-status=live}}</ref> Five days later, he marked his league debut with the [[Assist (association football)|assist]] for Reyna's opening goal in a 3–0 win over [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200919-haaland-and-reyna-shine-as-dortmund-youngsters-down-gladbach |title=Haaland and Reyna shine as Dortmund youngsters down Gladbach |website=France24 |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=19 September 2020 |access-date=20 September 2020 |archive-date=20 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920084218/https://www.france24.com/en/20200919-haaland-and-reyna-shine-as-dortmund-youngsters-down-gladbach |url-status=live}}</ref> and was named as [[2020–21 Bundesliga#Monthly awards|Bundesliga Rookie of the Month for September]].<ref name=RookieSep20/> When Bellingham faced [[SS Lazio|Lazio]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] on 20 October, aged 17 years and 113 days, he became the youngest Englishman to start a [[UEFA Champions League]] match, breaking the record previously set by [[Phil Foden]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54559710 |title=Lazio 3–1 Borussia Dortmund |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 October 2020 |access-date=21 October 2020 |archive-date=31 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031221103/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54559710 |url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Jude Bellingham 2020 (cropped2).jpg|thumb|upright|Bellingham playing for [[Borussia Dortmund]] in 2020]]

In the first three months of the season, Bellingham was a regular in all competitions, with six starts and seven substitute appearances in the Bundesliga as well as four Champions League starts.<ref name="Soccerway"/> He missed the first two matches of 2021 with a foot injury,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ruhrnachrichten.de/bvb/bvb-personal-bellingham-muss-weiter-pausieren-frust-bei-schmelzer-1589257.html |title=BVB-Personal: Bellingham muss weiter pausieren – Frust bei Schmelzer |language=de |trans-title=BVB team: Bellingham still out – frustration for Schmelzer |first=Dirk |last=Krampe |newspaper=Ruhr Nachrichten |location=Dortmund |date=4 January 2021 |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415112935/https://www.ruhrnachrichten.de/bvb/bvb-personal-bellingham-muss-weiter-pausieren-frust-bei-schmelzer-1589257.html |url-status=live}}</ref> but returned to action as an increasingly regular starter.<ref name="Soccerway" /> He scored his first Bundesliga goal from Reyna's knock-down to equalise with [[VfB Stuttgart]] early in the second half of a 3–2 win on 10 April.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bundesliga-jude-bellingham-and-ansgar-knauff-rescue-borussia-dortmund/a-57158326 |title=Bundesliga: Jude Bellingham and Ansgar Knauff rescue Borussia Dortmund |first=Matt |last=Ford |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=10 April 2021 |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415112930/https://www.dw.com/en/bundesliga-jude-bellingham-and-ansgar-knauff-rescue-borussia-dortmund/a-57158326 |url-status=live}}</ref> His first Champions League goal came four days later against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Quarter-finals|quarter-final second leg]], but Dortmund could not retain their [[away goals rule|away-goal]] advantage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/borussia-dortmund-vs-manchester-city/report/442558 |title=Borussia Dortmund 1–2 Man City (Agg: 2–4): Pep Guardiola reaches first Champions League semi-final with City |website=Sky Sports |date=15 April 2021 |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415112930/https://www.skysports.com/football/borussia-dortmund-vs-manchester-city/report/442558 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bellingham started in Dortmund's 4–1 victory over [[RB Leipzig]] in the [[2021 DFB-Pokal final]]. He was booked in the first half and replaced by [[Thorgan Hazard]] at half-time with his team 3–0 ahead.<ref name="2021 Pokal" /> He finished the season with 29 appearances and one goal in the Bundesliga, 46 appearances and four goals in all competitions,<ref name="Soccerway"/> and was voted [[Vereinigung der Vertragsfussballspieler#Newcomer of the Season (2010–present)|Newcomer of the Season by his fellow players]].<ref name="VdV2021" /> Bellingham was runner-up to [[Pedri]] of [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the 2021 [[Kopa Trophy]], awarded to the world's best under-21 male player as voted by previous winners of the [[Ballon d'Or]].<ref name="2021Kopa" /><ref name="AboutKopa">{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/soccer/kopa-trophy-what-is-it-nominees-and-who-has-won-it-before-n-2/ |title=Kopa Trophy: what is it, nominees and who has won it before |first=Calum |last=Roche |website=AS USA |date=30 October 2023 |access-date=5 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231105213306/https://en.as.com/soccer/kopa-trophy-what-is-it-nominees-and-who-has-won-it-before-n-2/ |archive-date=5 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

====2021–2023: Bundesliga Player of the Season and league runner-up====
On 4 December 2021, Bellingham played in ''[[Der Klassiker]]'' against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. He made the assists for both Dortmund goals,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59534910 |title=Borussia Dortmund 2–3 Bayern Munich |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 December 2021 |access-date=6 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105113321/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59534910 |archive-date=5 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> but Bayern won the match 3–2 via a 77th-minute penalty awarded after lengthy [[video assistant referee|VAR]] involvement. Earlier in the fixture, two Dortmund penalty appeals were turned down by referee [[Felix Zwayer]], who refused to review either.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/dortmund-left-fuming-over-bayerns-winning-penalty-decision-2021-12-04/ |title=Dortmund left fuming over Bayern's winning penalty decision |first=Karolos |last=Grohmann |editor-first=Ken |editor-last=Ferris |publisher=Reuters |date=5 December 2021 |access-date=6 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105111827/https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/dortmund-left-fuming-over-bayerns-winning-penalty-decision-2021-12-04/ |archive-date=5 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/dec/06/dortmund-and-bellingham-cry-foul-in-klassiker-but-old-failings-remain |title=Dortmund and Bellingham cry foul in Klassiker but old failings remain |first=Andy |last=Brassell |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=6 December 2021 |access-date=6 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221105111825/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/dec/06/dortmund-and-bellingham-cry-foul-in-klassiker-but-old-failings-remain |archive-date=5 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Interviewed live by [[Viaplay]] immediately after the match, Bellingham was critical of Zwayer's decisions, and made reference to his part in the [[2005 German football match-fixing scandal]], saying: "You give a referee, that has match fixed before, the biggest game in Germany. What do you expect?"<ref name=BBC6Dec/> The [[German Football Association]] (DFB) wrote to Bellingham asking for his comments as a matter of urgency,<ref name=BBC6Dec>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59548308 |title=Jude Bellingham: German FA investigating Borussia Dortmund and England midfielder's comments about referee |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 December 2021 |access-date=6 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211210033146/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59548308 |archive-date=10 December 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> and he was fined €40,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59564618 |title=Bellingham fined for referee comments |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 December 2021 |access-date=8 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230108170708/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59564618 |archive-date=8 January 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 22 October 2022, Bellingham scored twice in a 5–0 defeat of Stuttgart that put Borussia Dortmund into the top four; his first opened the scoring from a rapid attack that he both started and finished, his second was a skilfully curved shot early in the second half.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bellingham scores twice as Dortmund rout Stuttgart |publisher=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63360123 |date=22 October 2022 |access-date=15 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240508074827/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63360123 |archive-date=8 May 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the final day of the Bundesliga season, Dortmund needed to beat [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] to ensure the league title. Bellingham was on the bench because of an injured knee, and remained unused. Dortmund managed to draw after falling 2–0 behind, but Bayern Munich's 89th-minute winner against [[1. FC Köln]] was enough to put them ahead on [[goal difference]]. After the match, a tearful Bellingham pushed cameras away as he left the field.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65714772 |title=1. FC Köln 1 Bayern Munich 2 |first=Emlyn |last=Begley |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2023 |access-date=29 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240513081211/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65714772 |archive-date=13 May 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65714765 |title=Borussia Dortmund 2–2 Mainz 05: Dortmund expect 'brutal few days' after gifting Bayern Munich title |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2023 |access-date=4 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240513081447/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65714765 |archive-date=13 May 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> His performances earned him the [[2022–23 Bundesliga#Annual awards|Bundesliga Player of the Season]] award.<ref name="22/23 Bundesliga PotS" /> Having finished as runner-up two years prior, Bellingham won the [[2023 Ballon d'Or#Kopa Trophy|Kopa Trophy in 2023]] in recognition of his performances over the [[2022–23 Borussia Dortmund season|2022–23 season for Dortmund]] and for England in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. He became the first Englishman to receive the award, which was presented at the [[2023 Ballon d'Or]] ceremony in October.<ref name="2023Kopa" /> He placed 18th in the Ballon d'Or voting.<ref name="2023Kopa" />

===Real Madrid===
On 14 June 2023, [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] announced the signing of Bellingham on a six-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Announcement: Bellingham |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2023/06/14/official-announcement-bellingham |publisher=Real Madrid CF |date=14 June 2023 |access-date=14 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230825164458/https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2023/06/14/official-announcement-bellingham |archive-date=25 August 2023}}</ref> [[Borussia Dortmund]] would receive a base transfer fee of €103&nbsp;million with potential to rise by 30% to approximately €133.9&nbsp;million due to add-ons,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/soccer/the-add-ons-included-in-jude-bellinghams-move-from-borussia-dortmund-to-real-madrid-n/ |title=The add-ons included in Jude Bellingham's move from Borussia Dortmund to Real Madrid |first=Mario |last=de la Riva |website=Diario AS |date=23 June 2023 |access-date=22 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240414105251/https://en.as.com/soccer/the-add-ons-included-in-jude-bellinghams-move-from-borussia-dortmund-to-real-madrid-n/ |archive-date=14 April 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> from which a sell-on clause would earn Birmingham City around £6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Birmingham City get £6m from Jude Bellingham's move to Real Madrid |url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/birmingham-city-get-6m-from-jude-bellinghams-move-to-real-madrid-6v5sdl3sd |last1=Joyce |first1=Paul |last2=Lawton |first2=Matt |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=14 June 2023 |access-date=15 June 2023 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230614174151/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/birmingham-city-get-6m-from-jude-bellinghams-move-to-real-madrid-6v5sdl3sd |archive-date=14 June 2023}}</ref> He became the sixth Englishman to join Real Madrid in the professional era.<ref name="6th English">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/14/from-beckham-to-bale-british-players-real-madrid-jude-bellingham |title=From Beckham to Bale: the history of British players at Real Madrid |website=Guardian Sport |date=14 June 2023 |access-date=22 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231013202902/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/14/from-beckham-to-bale-british-players-real-madrid-jude-bellingham |archive-date=13 October 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn-ua|The previous five were [[Laurie Cunningham]], [[Steve McManaman]], [[David Beckham]], [[Michael Owen]] and [[Jonathan Woodgate]].<ref name="6th English" />}}

====2023–24: Debut season and goalscoring records====
On 12 August 2023, Bellingham marked his debut with a close-range [[half volley (association football)|half-volleyed]] goal from a [[corner kick]] in a 2–0 [[2023–24 La Liga|La Liga]] win away to [[Athletic Bilbao]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 August 2023 |title=Athletic Bilbao 0–2 Real Madrid: Jude Bellingham scores on his debut as Real win |publisher=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66489759 |url-status=live |access-date=12 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230906085918/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66489759 |archive-date=6 September 2023}}</ref> Two goals and an assist for [[Vinícius Júnior]] in a 3–1 victory at [[UD Almería|Almería]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66560805 |title=Almería 1–3 Real Madrid: Jude Bellingham scores twice as visitors maintain 100% La Liga start |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 August 2023 |access-date=19 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230826115029/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66560805 |archive-date=26 August 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the winner at [[Celta de Vigo|Celta Vigo]] in the two remaining August matches made him the league's top scorer and the first English recipient of the [[La Liga Player of the Month]] award.<ref name="La Liga Aug23 POTM" /> A 95th-minute winner against [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] on 2 September in his first match at the newly renovated [[Santiago Bernabéu Stadium|Santiago Bernabéu]] made Bellingham the third player (after [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] in the [[2009–10 Real Madrid CF season|2009–10 season]] and [[Pepillo (footballer, born 1933)|Pepillo]] in [[1959–60 Real Madrid CF season|1959–60]]) to score in each of his first four competitive appearances for the club.<ref name="Adaptation">{{Cite news |last=West |first=Andy |date=3 September 2023 |title=Jude Bellingham starring in early Real Madrid career with five goals in four games |publisher=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66696278 |access-date=3 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230923232721/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66696278 |archive-date=23 September 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bellingham scored 10 goals in his first 10 matches for Madrid, equalling Cristiano Ronaldo's goal tally after his first 10 games for the club in 2009.<ref name="10 in 10 all comps">{{Cite web |last=Wilson |first=Joseph |publisher=Associated Press |date=13 October 2023 |title=Bellingham matches Ronaldo's start at Real Madrid with 10 goals in first 10 games |url=https://apnews.com/article/real-madrid-osasuna-girona-4e04c1ea9168901d1c1d874a4fdcdabf |access-date=13 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240108100031/https://apnews.com/article/real-madrid-osasuna-girona-4e04c1ea9168901d1c1d874a4fdcdabf |archive-date=8 January 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 October, Bellingham scored a brace, including a stoppage-time winner, to secure Real Madrid a 2–1 away win against their rivals [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], making him the first Real Madrid player to score in their La Liga and Champions League debuts for the club and in [[El Clásico]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/barcelona-real-madrid-live-score-updates-result-el-clasico/la5YHHdNfN6k/yR9dCrNSSq84/ |title=How Jude Bellingham won Real Madrid El Clasico against Barcelona with a sensational performance: Bellingham of the Bernabeu does it at Montjuic |first=Dermot |last=Corrigan |website=The Athletic |date=28 October 2023 |access-date=5 June 2024 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240605130405/https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/barcelona-real-madrid-live-score-updates-result-el-clasico/la5YHHdNfN6k/yR9dCrNSSq84/ |archive-date=5 June 2024}}</ref> His first goal, scored from {{convert|30|yds}}<ref name="Clasico BBC 2023">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67251678 |title=Jude Bellingham & Harry Kane: Are England stars world's two best players right now? |first=Joe |last=Rindl |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 October 2023 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031202450/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67251678 |archive-date=31 October 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> was his club's 300th in El Clásico and made him the first Englishman to score in that fixture since Michael Owen in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-kw/news/jude-bellingham-unstoppable-real-madrid-superstar-scores-golazo-real-madrid-first-clasico-appearance/blt89117e6a8dc1beaa |title=WATCH: Jude Bellingham is unstoppable! Real Madrid superstar scores twice against Barcelona on first Clasico appearance |first=Gill |last=Clark |website=Goal.com |date=28 October 2023 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231029011602/https://www.goal.com/en-kw/news/jude-bellingham-unstoppable-real-madrid-superstar-scores-golazo-real-madrid-first-clasico-appearance/blt89117e6a8dc1beaa |archive-date=29 October 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> Bellingham set several records with these goals.{{efn-ua|Bellingham became the first player to score a brace in his first El Clásico since [[:es:Pedro María Arsuaga|Pedro Arsuaga]] in 1947,<ref name="Football Espana" /> and the fourth player under 21 years old to score multiple goals in that encounter in La Liga, following [[Jaime Lazcano]] in 1930, Arsuaga in 1947 and [[Lionel Messi]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ESPNStatsInfo |author=ESPN Stats & Info |number=1718299992954171661 |title=Jude Bellingham is the 4th player with multiple goals in an ELCLÁSICO played in LALIGA before turning 21 years old, joining Lionel Messi in 2007, Pedro Arsuaga in 1947 and Jaime Lazcano in 1930. |date=28 October 2023 |access-date=5 June 2024}}</ref> His ten goals from his first ten league matches exceeded Cristiano Ronaldo's tally of seven for Madrid in 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/j12429.html?temp=2009-10&mf&cat=1a |title=Cristiano Ronaldo: Matches: 2009–10: First Division |website=BDFutbol |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240605110527/https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/j12429.html?temp=2009-10&mf&cat=1a |url-status=live }}</ref> and equalled the most league goals scored in a single season by [[Zinedine Zidane]] across an 18-year career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe12757/zinedine-zidane/club-matches/ |title=Zinédine Zidane » Club matches |website=worldfootball.net |date=17 February 2023 |publisher=HeimSpiel Medien |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-date=9 October 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241009133124/https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/zinedine-zidane/2/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Bellingham's 13 goals from his first 13 games at the club equalled the starts of Cristiano Ronaldo and [[Alfredo Di Stéfano]].<ref name="Football Espana">{{Cite web |last=Barlow |first=Ruairidh |date=30 October 2023 |title=Jude Bellingham outstripping series of Real Madrid legends including Cristiano Ronaldo |url=https://www.football-espana.net/2023/10/30/jude-bellingham-outstripping-series-of-real-madrid-legends-as |website=Football España |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101055900/https://www.football-espana.net/2023/10/30/jude-bellingham-outstripping-series-of-real-madrid-legends-as |archive-date=1 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>}} His coach [[Carlo Ancelotti]] commented: "He seems like a veteran, the goal to level it totally changed the game... Today he was stupendous and shocked everyone with his wonderful goal from the edge of the area."<ref name="Clasico BBC 2023" /> Bellingham was named La Liga Player of the Month for October.<ref name="La Liga Oct23 POTM" />

Having received the Kopa Trophy a few weeks earlier,<ref name="2023Kopa" /> Bellingham was named winner of the [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]] for 2023, an award made to the best male under-21 footballer playing in the European top divisions over a calendar year.<ref name="2023 GoldenBoy" /> Bellingham dislocated his left shoulder on 5 November, and returned to action against [[Cádiz CF|Cádiz]] three weeks later only because of an injury crisis at the club. Wearing heavy strapping, he assisted the first goal and scored the third of a 3–0 win, which took Madrid top of the table and his personal total to 14 from his first 15 games, breaking the club record held jointly by [[Pruden]], [[Alfredo Di Stéfano]] and Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5091132/2023/11/27/jude-bellingham-real-madrid-cadiz/ |title=Jude Bellingham is Real Madrid's star, even while nursing a shoulder injury |first=Guillermo |last=Rai |website=The Athletic |date=27 November 2023 |access-date=27 November 2023 |url-access=registration |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231127174849/https://theathletic.com/5091132/2023/11/27/jude-bellingham-real-madrid-cadiz/ |archive-date=27 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="BBC 14 in 15">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67538934 |title=Cádiz 0–3 Real Madrid |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 November 2023 |access-date=27 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231129220759/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67538934 |archive-date=29 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a 4–2 victory against [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] on 29 November, Bellingham became the first player to score in each of his first four Champions League appearances for Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67571134 |title=Real Madrid 4–2 Napoli |first=Joe |last=Rindl |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 November 2023 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240424205059/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67571134 |archive-date=24 April 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Bellingham scored twice in a 4–0 win over La Liga title race rivals [[Girona FC|Girona]] on 10 February 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/jude-bellingham-brace-helps-la-liga-leaders-real-madrid-crush-title-rivals-girona/articleshow/107595050.cms |title=Jude Bellingham brace helps La Liga leaders Real Madrid crush title rivals Girona |newspaper=The Times of India |date=11 February 2024 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240225184831/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/jude-bellingham-brace-helps-la-liga-leaders-real-madrid-crush-title-rivals-girona/articleshow/107595050.cms |archive-date=25 February 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> He was sent off for protesting at the end of Real Madrid's 2–2 draw with [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] at the [[Mestalla Stadium|Mestalla]] on 2 March after what would have been his winning goal was denied because referee [[Jesús Gil Manzano]] had blown the whistle to end the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68460081 |title=Bellingham sent off after full-time in Real draw |first=Bobbie |last=Jackson |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2024 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316071318/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68460081 |archive-date=16 March 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5307902/2024/03/03/bellingham-goal-ruled-out-what-happened/ |title=Explained: Bellingham's 99th-minute red card and the goal that never was |last=Corrigan |first=Dermot |website=The Athletic |date=2 March 2024 |access-date=4 March 2024 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240304163611/https://theathletic.com/5307902/2024/03/03/bellingham-goal-ruled-out-what-happened/ |archive-date=4 March 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> He scored the winner in added time as Real Madrid won El Clásico 3–2 at home on 21 April;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68869328 |title=Real Madrid 3–2 Barcelona: Jude Bellingham scores late to seal El Clasico win |last=Jackson |first=Bobbie |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 April 2024 |access-date=22 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240522211221/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68869328 |archive-date=22 May 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> it was his 21st goal of the season, and made him Madrid's all-time top English scorer, overtaking [[Laurie Cunningham]] and [[David Beckham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportsbrief.com/football/63547-jude-bellingham-passes-david-beckham-goals-scored-by-englishman-real-madrid-colours/ |title=Jude Bellingham passes David Beckham for most goals scored by an Englishman in Real Madrid colours |first=Joel |last=Reyes |website=Sports Brief |date=22 April 2024 |access-date=5 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240424131950/https://sportsbrief.com/football/63547-jude-bellingham-passes-david-beckham-goals-scored-by-englishman-real-madrid-colours/ |archive-date=24 April 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> The following day he was named as winner of the 2024 [[Laureus World Sports Award for Breakthrough of the Year]].<ref name="Laureus Breakthrough"/> He concluded his domestic season as Real Madrid's top league scorer with 19 goals and 6 assists as they won the La Liga title, a performance that earned him the [[La Liga Awards#Player of the season|La Liga Player of the Season]] award.<ref name="Liga PotS" /> Facing his former club Borussia Dortmund in the [[2024 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]], Bellingham produced the assist for Vinícius Júnior to complete a 2–0 win.<ref name="UCL 2324"/> With four goals, five assists and a passing accuracy of 90.5%, Bellingham was named the UEFA Champions League Young Player of the Season.<ref name="UCL 2324 YPotS" /> His performances were recognised with third-place finishes in both of that year's major polls, the [[2024 Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] and [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2024#The Best FIFA Men's Player|The Best FIFA Men's Player]].<ref name="2024 Ballon d'Or">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/oct/28/rodri-and-bonmati-scoop-ballons-dor-as-real-madrid-boycott-big-awards-night |title=Rodri and Bonmatí scoop Ballons d'Or as Real Madrid boycott big awards night |first=Nick |last=Ames |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2024 |access-date=13 March 2025 |archive-date=13 February 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250213154943/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/oct/28/rodri-and-bonmati-scoop-ballons-dor-as-real-madrid-boycott-big-awards-night |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="FIFA The Best 2024">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/the-best-fifa-football-awards/2024/articles/mens-player-2024-winner-vinicius-jr |title=Vinicius Jr named The Best Men's Player |publisher=FIFA |date=16 December 2024 |access-date=13 March 2025 |archive-date=17 December 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241217181603/https://www.fifa.com/en/the-best-fifa-football-awards/2024/articles/mens-player-2024-winner-vinicius-jr |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2024–25: Second season and European Super Cup====
[[File:2025 04 26 Final de la Copa del Rey - 54482387776 (Vinícius Júnior, Jude Bellingham e Rodrygo Goés) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Vinícius Júnior]], Bellingham and [[Rodrygo]] lining up for [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the [[2025 Copa del Rey final]]]]

On 14 August 2024, Bellingham started his second season in Spain, providing the assist for his new Real teammate [[Kylian Mbappé]]'s debut goal, as Madrid defeated [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]] 2–0 to win a [[List of UEFA Super Cup finals#Performances|record-breaking]] sixth European Super Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Real Madrid 2–0 Atalanta: Mbappé scores as Los Blancos claim Super Cup|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/news/0290-1b9cb774481e-880cbe608abf-1000--real-madrid-2-0-atalanta-mbappe-scores-as-los-blancos-claim/|publisher=UEFA|date=14 August 2024|access-date=14 August 2024|archive-date=14 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240814213305/https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/news/0290-1b9cb774481e-880cbe608abf-1000--real-madrid-2-0-atalanta-mbappe-scores-as-los-blancos-claim/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 November, Bellingham scored his first goal of the season and first for Madrid since May 2024 in a dominant 4–0 home win over [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Thomas|first=Marissa|title=Real Madrid 4–0 Osasuna: Vinícius Júnior hits hat-trick but Éder Militão tears ACL|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cn7mdm71emzt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 November 2024|access-date=9 November 2024|archive-date=9 November 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241109212850/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cn7mdm71emzt|url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next month, he scored league goals against [[CD Leganés|Leganés]],<ref>{{Cite web|last=Coates|first=Charlotte|title=Leganés 0–3 Real Madrid: Kylian Mbappé and Jude Bellingham score as visitors close gap on Barca|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c78dkp0gkz0t|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 November 2024|access-date=24 November 2024|archive-date=24 November 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241124210408/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c78dkp0gkz0t|url-status=live}}</ref> Getafe,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Thomas|first=Marissa|title=Bellingham & Mbappé score as Real Madrid beat Getafe|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c774p71xxk5t|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 December 2024|access-date=1 December 2024|archive-date=1 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241201180156/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c774p71xxk5t|url-status=live}}</ref> Athletic Bilbao and Girona.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Coates|first=Charlotte|title=Athletic Bilbao 2–1 Real Madrid: Jude Bellingham scores but Real Madrid lose in La Liga|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c20602dx55nt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 December 2024|access-date=4 December 2024|archive-date=10 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241210225308/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c20602dx55nt|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Girona 0–3 Real Madrid: Jude Bellingham and Kylian Mbappé score in La Liga win|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c5y485lq61nt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 December 2024|access-date=7 December 2024|archive-date=10 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241210225404/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c5y485lq61nt|url-status=live}}</ref> On 14 December, Bellingham got on the scoresheet in a 3–3 draw at [[Rayo Vallecano]], extending his scoring streak to six consecutive La Liga matches, becoming the first Real Madrid player to achieve the feat since [[Karim Benzema]] in [[2015–16 Real Madrid CF season|2016]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Jude Bellingham scores again but Real Madrid held to draw by Rayo Vallecano in thriller|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cvgmprx5kxrt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 December 2024|access-date=14 December 2024|archive-date=14 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241214222737/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cvgmprx5kxrt|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this streak, he was named Player of the Month in La Liga for December.<ref name="december potm">{{cite news|url=https://www.laliga.com/en-GB/news/jude-bellingham-laliga-ea-sports-player-of-the-month-for-december|date=27 December 2024|title=Jude Bellingham, LALIGA EA SPORTS Player of the Month for December|access-date=27 December 2024|archive-date=27 December 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241227210857/https://www.laliga.com/en-GB/news/jude-bellingham-laliga-ea-sports-player-of-the-month-for-december|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 February 2025, Bellingham received a two-match suspension following his red card in Madrid's 1–1 draw with Osasuna. He was dismissed for dissent after protesting a refereeing decision, with the match official later reporting that Bellingham had used offensive language towards him. Manager Carlo Ancelotti stated that the referee, [[José Luis Munuera Montero]], accused Bellingham of shouting "f*** you," whereas Bellingham claimed he had actually said "f*** off" in frustration rather than as a direct insult. Initially facing a potential 12-game ban under Spanish FA regulations, his suspension was reduced to two matches after the governing body ruled that his actions were "disrespectful/inconsiderate" rather than abusive.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Jude Bellingham red card: Real Madrid midfielder banned for two games over 'disrespect' towards referee|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11835/13312610/jude-bellingham-red-card-real-madrid-midfielder-banned-for-two-games-over-disrespect-towards-referee|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 February 2025|access-date=20 March 2025|archive-date=20 March 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250320110630/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11835/13312610/jude-bellingham-red-card-real-madrid-midfielder-banned-for-two-games-over-disrespect-towards-referee|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2025–26: Shoulder surgery====
On 16 July 2025, Real Madrid confirmed that Bellingham had successfully undergone surgery to address a long-standing dislocation of his left shoulder, an issue he had battled since November 2023.<ref>{{cite news |date=16 July 2025 |title=Bellingham medical report |publisher=Real Madrid CF |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en-US/news/football/first-team/medical-reports/parte-medico-de-bellingham-16-07-2025 |access-date=22 July 2025}}</ref> According to reports, Bellingham was expected to be sidelined for approximately 10 to 12 weeks, missing the start of the [[2025–26 La Liga]] season as well as the early stages of the UEFA Champions League group phase and aiming for an October return.<ref>{{cite news |date=16 July 2025 |title=Jude Bellingham targeting October return following shoulder surgery |publisher=The Athletic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6484232/2025/07/15/jude-bellingham-shoulder-surgery-october-return/ |access-date=22 July 2025}}</ref> However, Bellingham returned to action earlier, featuring in Madrid's 2–0 win over [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] on 20 September.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Millington|first=Adam|title=Real Madrid 2–0 Espanyol: Kylian Mbappé scores again as Real continue winning run|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cpw17y5rg71t|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 September 2025|access-date=20 September 2025|archive-date=20 September 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250920173741/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cpw17y5rg71t|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 October, he scored his first goal of the season, which turned out to be the winner in a 1–0 Champions League victory over [[Juventus FC|Juventus]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Anderson|first=Jess|title=Real Madrid 1–0 Juventus: Jude Bellingham scores first goal of season in Real win|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cr43rxk47qwt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 October 2025|access-date=23 October 2025|archive-date=23 October 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20251023103749/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cr43rxk47qwt|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 October, the following weekend, Bellingham scored his first La Liga goal of the season, which turned out to be the winner – his third match-winner against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in his Real Madrid career.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lowe |first=Sid |author-link=Sid Lowe |date=2025-10-26 |title=Bellingham scores clásico winner as Real Madrid pull clear of Barcelona |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/oct/26/real-madrid-barcelona-el-clasico-la-liga-match-report |access-date=2025-10-26 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth career===
Bellingham was eligible to play for his native England and also for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], for which he qualified via a grandparent.<ref name="auto"/> He made his England under-15 debut against Turkey in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theathletic.co.uk/1461690/2019/12/24/a-generation-unlike-any-we-have-seen-before-englands-teenage-stars-of-the-future/ |title=A generation unlike any we have seen before: England's teenage stars of the future |first=Jack |last=Pitt-Brooke |work=The Athletic |date=29 December 2019 |access-date=5 July 2020 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=5 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200705031747/https://theathletic.co.uk/1461690/2019/12/24/a-generation-unlike-any-we-have-seen-before-englands-teenage-stars-of-the-future/ |url-status=live}}</ref> In recognition of his [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] that team during the 2017–18 season, he was presented with a Special Achievement Award at the 2018 Birmingham City Academy awards night.<ref name=awards>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/archive/lubala-and-harding-at-blues-academy-awards |title=Lubala and Harding at Blues Academy Awards |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=17 May 2018 |access-date=3 September 2022 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030127/https://bcfc.com/news/articles/2018/lubala-and-harding-at-blues-academy-awards/ |url-status=live}}</ref> By the end of 2018 he had made his first appearance for the [[England national under-16 football team|England under-16 team]], and went on to feature in eleven games, score four goals, and captain the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfcacademy.com/media/upload/files/Academy-Highlights-of-the-Month---Nov-%26-Dec%284%29.pdf |title=Academy highlights of the month: November and December 2018 |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. Academy |access-date=1 September 2019 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030124/https://www.bcfcacademy.com/media/upload/files/Academy-Highlights-of-the-Month---Nov-%26-Dec%284%29.pdf |url-status=usurped}}</ref><ref name=BeSoccer>{{cite web |url=https://www.besoccer.com/player/career-path/j-bellingham-839567 |title=Jude Bellingham's career |website=BeSoccer |access-date=7 June 2024 |archive-date=8 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240608134814/https://www.besoccer.com/player/career-path/j-bellingham-839567 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was included in [[England national under-17 football team|England's under-17 squad]] for the Syrenka Cup, a [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly tournament]] held in September 2019 in preparation for the [[2020 UEFA European Under-17 Championship qualification|2020 European Championship qualifiers]] the following March.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2019/aug/30/england-u17s-squad-named-for-poland-trip-300819 |title=New England MU17s boss Kevin Betsy will take his squad to Poland for the Syrenka Cup |publisher=The Football Association |first=Nicholas |last=Veevers |date=30 August 2019 |access-date=1 September 2019 |archive-date=11 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210211030141/https://www.thefa.com/news/2019/aug/30/england-u17s-squad-named-for-poland-trip-300819 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut as a substitute in England's opening match of the tournament, a 5–0 win over [[Finland national under-17 football team|Finland]] in which he scored the third goal,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/match-report/ma8988500/lineup/ |title=U17 Friendlies 2019: September: England–Finland 5:0 |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL |access-date=9 September 2019 |archive-date=16 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216161204/https://www.worldfootball.net/report/u17-h-freundschaft-2019-september-england-finnland/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and captained the team in their second fixture, in which they came back from a goal behind to beat [[Austria national under-17 football team|Austria]] 4–2 and qualify for the final. Again, Bellingham scored the third goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2019/sep/09/england-mu17s-4-2-austria-090919 |title=Young Lions come back from behind to beat Austria and secure Syrenka Cup Final spot |first=Nicholas |last=Veevers |publisher=The Football Association |date=8 September 2019 |access-date=9 September 2019 |archive-date=14 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914090826/http://www.thefa.com/news/2019/sep/09/england-mu17s-4-2-austria-090919 |url-status=live}}</ref> He retained the captaincy for the final, in which England beat hosts [[Poland national under-17 football team|Poland]] on [[penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] following a 2–2 draw,<ref name=Syrenka/> and was named player of the tournament.<ref name=Syrenka2>{{cite web |url=https://junior.weszlo.com/2019/09/10/puchar-syrenki-u-17-przegrywamy-po-karnych-z-anglia/ |title=Puchar Syrenki U-17: Przegrywamy po karnych z Anglią |language=pl |trans-title=U17 Syrenka Cup: We lose to England on penalties |website=WESZŁO! |date=10 September 2019 |access-date=15 September 2019 |archive-date=5 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200805022236/https://junior.weszlo.com/2019/09/10/puchar-syrenki-u-17-przegrywamy-po-karnych-z-anglia/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Bellingham received his first call-up to the [[England national under-21 football team|under-21 squad]] for [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|European Championship qualifiers]] against [[Kosovo national under-21 football team|Kosovo]] and [[Austria national under-21 football team|Austria]] in September 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12056822/jude-bellingham-england-u21-boss-aidy-boothroyd-selects-borussia-dortmund-midfielder |title=Jude Bellingham: England U21 boss Aidy Boothroyd selects Borussia Dortmund midfielder |first=Dan |last=Sansom |website=Sky Sports |date=26 August 2020 |access-date=26 August 2020 |archive-date=27 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200827092458/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12056822/jude-bellingham-england-u21-boss-aidy-boothroyd-selects-borussia-dortmund-midfielder |url-status=live}}</ref> He became the youngest player to appear for England U21 when he came on to replace [[Tom Davies (footballer, born 1998)|Tom Davies]] after 62 minutes of the match against Kosovo on 4 September with England 3–0 ahead, and scored after 85 minutes to complete the 6–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54023955 |title=Kosovo U21 0–6 England U21 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 September 2020 |access-date=4 September 2020 |archive-date=7 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200907053205/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54023955 |url-status=live}}</ref>

===Senior career===
[[File:2022 FIFA World Cup - Bellingham (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Bellingham playing for [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]

In November 2020, after [[James Ward-Prowse]] and [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]] withdrew through injury, Bellingham was called up to the [[England national football team|England senior squad]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54885682 |title=Jude Bellingham: England call up Borussia Dortmund teenager to senior squad for first time |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2020 |access-date=13 November 2020 |archive-date=13 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113073206/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54885682 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his debut in a friendly match against the Republic of Ireland at Wembley on 12 November,<ref name="BBC intl debut">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819958 |title=England 3–0 Republic of Ireland: Jude Bellingham makes debut at 17 |first=Phil |last=McNulty |author-link=Phil McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 November 2020 |access-date=21 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119003127/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819958 |archive-date=19 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> replacing Mason Mount after 73 minutes of a 3–0 win.<ref name="Sky intl debut" /> At 17 years, 136 days, he became England's third-youngest full international; only Theo Walcott and Wayne Rooney had appeared at a younger age.<ref name="Sky intl debut">{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/england-vs-rep-ire/report/439477 |title=England 3–0 Republic of Ireland: Jack Grealish shines in Wembley friendly win |first=Ben |last=Grounds |website=Sky Sports |date=13 November 2020 |access-date=21 August 2024 |archive-date=13 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113071931/https://www.skysports.com/football/england-vs-rep-ire/report/439477 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Bellingham was named in the England squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2020]] tournament, which was delayed until 2021 because of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57321188 |title=Euro 2020: Trent Alexander-Arnold named in England's 26-man squad |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2021 |access-date=1 June 2021 |archive-date=1 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210601214201/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/57321188 |url-status=live}}</ref> When he came on as an 82nd-minute substitute in England's opening match, a 1–0 win over [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] at Wembley on 13 June, aged 17 years and 349 days, he became both the youngest Englishman to play at any major tournament and the youngest of any nationality to play at a [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51197735 |title=England 1–0 Croatia |first=Phil |last=McNulty |author-link=Phil McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 June 2021 |access-date=15 June 2021 |archive-date=24 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624235743/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51197735 |url-status=live}}</ref> the latter record was broken by [[Poland national football team|Poland]]'s [[Kacper Kozłowski (footballer)|Kacper Kozłowski]] just six days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/poland-starlet-kozlowski-breaks-bellinghams-euros-record-for/7egeo0cke1rd1ts92qpvuuztt |title=Poland starlet Kozlowski breaks Bellingham's Euros record for youngest-ever player just six days after it was set |first=Andrew |last=Steel |website=Goal |date=19 June 2021 |access-date=20 June 2021 |archive-date=20 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210620000406/https://www.goal.com/en/news/poland-starlet-kozlowski-breaks-bellinghams-euros-record-for/7egeo0cke1rd1ts92qpvuuztt |url-status=live}}</ref>

Bellingham scored his first senior international goal in England's 6–2 victory over [[Iran national football team|Iran]] in their first game of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] on 21 November. This made him the second youngest scorer for England at a World Cup. He also made the run and pass to [[Harry Kane]] who crossed for [[Raheem Sterling]] to score England's third goal, and played the through ball from which [[Callum Wilson]] set up their sixth for [[Jack Grealish]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12752361/jude-bellingham-and-bukayo-saka-show-the-way-forward-as-gareth-southgate-unleashes-england-against-iran |title=Jude Bellingham and Bukayo Saka show the way forward as Gareth Southgate unleashes England against Iran |first=Nick |last=Wright |website=Sky Sports |date=22 November 2022 |access-date=23 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123121237/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12752361/jude-bellingham-and-bukayo-saka-show-the-way-forward-as-gareth-southgate-unleashes-england-against-iran |archive-date=23 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/23/jude-bellingham-england-game-changer-world-cup-qatar-gareth-southgate |title=Jude Bellingham: England's gamechanger who does not do doubts |first=Jacob |last=Sternberg |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=23 November 2022 |access-date=23 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221129143124/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/23/jude-bellingham-england-game-changer-world-cup-qatar-gareth-southgate |archive-date=29 November 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> He followed this up during the last-16 game against Senegal with a run through the defence, assisting [[Jordan Henderson]]'s goal in the 38th minute, and played a key role in Harry Kane's goal in first-half [[stoppage time]], setting up Phil Foden to make the assist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/england-vs-senegal-world-cup-2022-live-score-updates-result/XEQplJmpWTsT/zysGtM1oVwny/ |title=Story of the game |first=Jacob |last=Whitehead |website=The Athletic |date=4 December 2022 |access-date=7 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240607140455/https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/england-vs-senegal-world-cup-2022-live-score-updates-result/XEQplJmpWTsT/zysGtM1oVwny/ |archive-date=7 June 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

===UEFA Euro 2024===
Bellingham was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240607013843/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |archive-date=7 June 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> His powerful header from [[Bukayo Saka]]'s deflected cross gave "The Three Lions" a 1–0 victory against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]], and he was named player of the match.<ref name="Euro24 Serbia" />

He scored with a 95th-minute [[overhead kick]] in the [[round of 16]] against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] to tie the scores at 1–1 and take the match into extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40468071/euro-2024-england-kane-lauds-incredible-jude-bellingham-goal |title=Euro 2024: England's Kane lauds incredible Jude Bellingham goal |work=ESPN |date=30 June 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240701095912/https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40468071/euro-2024-england-kane-lauds-incredible-jude-bellingham-goal |archive-date=1 July 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> England won 2–1, and Bellingham was again named player of the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b41ff0c9b9e-382c1ab22a1d-1000--england-2-1-slovakia-after-extra-time-bellingham-and-kane-e/ |title=England 2–1 Slovakia (after extra time): Bellingham and Kane earn comeback victory |publisher=UEFA |date=30 June 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240819152942/https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b41ff0c9b9e-382c1ab22a1d-1000--england-2-1-slovakia-after-extra-time-bellingham-and-kane-e/ |archive-date=19 August 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> After scoring the equaliser, Bellingham gestured towards the opposing [[substitute (association football)|substitutes' bench]] by grabbing his crotch, claiming it was an inside joke aimed at "some close friends".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/jude-bellingham-faces-uefa-disciplinary-investigation-over-conduct-in-england-win-over-slovakia-at-euro-2024-13157788 |title=Jude Bellingham investigated over gesture he made after wonder goal against Slovakia |website=Sky News |date=2 July 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240705233605/https://news.sky.com/story/jude-bellingham-faces-uefa-disciplinary-investigation-over-conduct-in-england-win-over-slovakia-at-euro-2024-13157788 |archive-date=5 July 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> After an investigation, [[UEFA]] found he had "violat[ed] the basic rules of decent conduct", fined him €30,000 and imposed a one-match ban suspended for 12 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/05/jude-bellingham-fined-suspended-one-game-ban-for-gesture-england-slovakia-uefa-euro-2024 |title=Jude Bellingham fined €30,000 and given suspended one-game ban for gesture |first=Jacob |last=Steinberg |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 July 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240818162635/https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/05/jude-bellingham-fined-suspended-one-game-ban-for-gesture-england-slovakia-uefa-euro-2024 |archive-date=18 August 2024 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Bellingham played the full 120 minutes of the quarter-final against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], and scored the second kick of the penalty shootout which England won 5–3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b4e143fd946-8d1c55ab8bed-1000--england-1-1-switzerland-aet-5-3-pens-pickford-and-saka-l/ |title=England 1–1 Switzerland (5–3 pens): Pickford and Saka lead England to semi-finals |publisher=UEFA |date=6 July 2024 |access-date=7 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240707045212/https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b4e143fd946-8d1c55ab8bed-1000--england-1-1-switzerland-aet-5-3-pens-pickford-and-saka-l/ |archive-date=7 July 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> England reached [[UEFA Euro 2024 final|the final]], in which they faced [[Spain national men's football team|Spain]], who took the lead shortly after half-time. Bellingham touched Saka's pass to [[Cole Palmer]] who equalised after 73 minutes, but Spain scored a late winner and England ended the tournament as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2024/07/14/england-vs-spain-euro-2024-final-live-score-latest-updates/ |title=England suffer agonising defeat after Spain score winning goal in dying minutes of Euro 2024 final |first=Jason |last=Burt |website=The Telegraph |date=15 July 2024 |access-date=19 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240717205413/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2024/07/14/england-vs-spain-euro-2024-final-live-score-latest-updates/ |archive-date=17 July 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Player profile==
Known for his exceptional control of the ball, his physicality and his technical quality, Bellingham is often regarded as one of the best and most well-rounded midfielders in the world.<ref name="Guardian Lowe 202306">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/08/football-jude-bellingham-real-madrid-england-dortmund |title=Jude Bellingham is 19 years old but ready to be Real Madrid's everything |last=Lowe |first=Sid |author-link=Sid Lowe |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=8 June 2023 |access-date=3 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610144409/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jun/08/football-jude-bellingham-real-madrid-england-dortmund |archive-date=10 June 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thetrivelaeffect.com/how-good-is-jude-bellingham-an-analysis-of-his-playing-style-strengths-and-weaknesses/ |title=How good is Jude Bellingham? An analysis of his playing style, strengths, and weaknesses |last=Parvizi |first=Kevin |website=The Trivela Effect |date=27 May 2023 |access-date=3 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231110194203/https://thetrivelaeffect.com/how-good-is-jude-bellingham-an-analysis-of-his-playing-style-strengths-and-weaknesses/ |archive-date=10 November 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Lahm">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/may/04/jude-bellingham-next-step-join-greats-borussia-dortmund |title=Jude Bellingham is a fascinating talent: the next step is to join football's greats |last=Lahm |first=Philipp |author-link=Philipp Lahm |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=4 May 2023 |access-date=3 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231029154549/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/may/04/jude-bellingham-next-step-join-greats-borussia-dortmund |archive-date=29 October 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="The Analyst 202306">{{Cite web |url=https://theanalyst.com/2023/06/jude-bellingham-real-madrid-transfer/ |title=Is Jude Bellingham ready for Real Madrid? |last=Bissett |first=Luke |website=The Analyst |date=19 June 2023 |access-date=27 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231127175139/https://theanalyst.com/2023/06/jude-bellingham-real-madrid-transfer/ |archive-date=27 November 2023}}</ref><ref name="FIFA Colbert 202311" /> He is also known for his versatility and vision.<ref name="Guardian Lowe 202306" /><ref name="Bundesliga Smith 202306">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/is-england-s-jude-bellingham-the-world-s-best-midfielder-dortmund-real-madrid-transfer-22027 |title=How Real Madrid-bound Jude Bellingham became one of the world's best midfielders at Borussia Dortmund |first=Andy |last=Smith |publisher=Bundesliga |date=14 June 2023 |access-date=27 November 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240607142911/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/is-england-s-jude-bellingham-the-world-s-best-midfielder-dortmund-real-madrid-transfer-22027 |archive-date=7 June 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="FIFA Colbert 202311">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/world-class-skills-jude-bellingham |title=World-class skills: Jude Bellingham |last=Colbert |first=Tony |publisher=FIFA |date=15 November 2023 |access-date=15 November 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240607145819/https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/world-class-skills-jude-bellingham |archive-date=7 June 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> He is praised for fulfilling multiple positions and his dynamic playing style, playing both exceptional defence and attack, described by ''The Analyst'' as a "do-it-all midfielder".<ref name="The Analyst 202306" /> His excellent runs and dribbling abilities have also earned him praise, as have his keen ability to quickly transition from defence to attack.<ref name="The Analyst 202306" /> An analysis by Andy Smith for the [[Bundesliga]] described Bellingham as "the complete package: a dynamic midfielder who can win the ball and drive it forward, hold up possession, resist the press, find gaps in opposition defences, plus assist and score goals".<ref name="Bundesliga Smith 202306" /> Bellingham has been described by [[Philipp Lahm]] as a "complete midfielder", who can "dribble, pass, shoot and has the urge to score", and who is "physical and fearless, holds his ground in challenges and wins the ball".<ref name="Lahm" /> [[Phil Foden]] described Bellingham as "one of the most gifted players I've ever seen".<ref name="FIFA Colbert 202311" /> [[Paul Scholes]] also praised Bellingham in 2023, saying that "I think Jude Bellingham for his age and what he's accomplished so far in his short career, he's better than anything we've seen".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/Bellingham-scholes-real-madrid-man-united/bltc421c9c8ac3d946f |title='Better than anything we've seen' – Jude Bellingham praised by Paul Scholes who says midfielder did the 'right thing' not signing for Man Utd |last=Rowe |first=Patrick |website=Goal.com |date=12 October 2023 |access-date=27 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224234055/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/Bellingham-scholes-real-madrid-man-united/bltc421c9c8ac3d946f |archive-date=24 February 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> He has been widely compared to the likes of [[Zinedine Zidane]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67005713 |title='A little Di Stefano, a little Zidane' |last=Cryer |first=Andy |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 October 2023 |access-date=24 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240124001637/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67005713 |archive-date=24 January 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/roberto-carlos-real-madrid-legends-jude-bellingham-zinedine-zidane-england-star/blt6d3d379150854858 |title=Roberto Carlos reveals the three Real Madrid legends Jude Bellingham reminds him of – including Zinedine Zidane – as he praises the England star's 'personality' after incredible start to life in Spain |last=Mukherjee |first=Soham |website=Goal.com |date=9 November 2023 |access-date=24 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224234055/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/roberto-carlos-real-madrid-legends-jude-bellingham-zinedine-zidane-england-star/blt6d3d379150854858 |archive-date=24 February 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/39008052/real-madrid-bellingham-comparisons-legend-zidane |title=Real Madrid's Bellingham draws comparisons with legend Zidane |last1=Kirkland |first1=Alex |last2=Faez |first2=Rodrigo |website=ESPN |date=29 November 2023 |access-date=24 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240227003418/https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/39008052/real-madrid-bellingham-comparisons-legend-zidane |archive-date=27 February 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Following his move to Madrid in 2023, Bellingham took on a more advanced role in the midfield, often being positioned in the number 10 position as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], or even as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false 9]] or [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]] on occasion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/best-position-jude-bellingham-explains-style-evolved-admiration-real-madrid-luka-modric-toni-kroos/blt8c4e2a681d3c507a |title=Best position? Jude Bellingham explains how his style has evolved over the years as he reveals admiration for Real Madrid veterans Luka Modric & Toni Kroos |first=Chris |last=Burton |website=Goal.com |date=11 April 2024 |access-date=17 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240417205025/https://www.goal.com/en/lists/best-position-jude-bellingham-explains-style-evolved-admiration-real-madrid-luka-modric-toni-kroos/blt8c4e2a681d3c507a |archive-date=17 April 2024 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.football-espana.net/2023/07/04/carlo-ancelotti-to-experiment-with-new-jude-bellingham-position-at-real-madrid |title=Carlo Ancelotti to experiment with new Jude Bellingham position at Real Madrid |last=Barlow |first=Ruairidh |website=Football España |date=4 July 2023 |access-date=17 April 2024 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240509134956/https://www.football-espana.net/2023/07/04/carlo-ancelotti-to-experiment-with-new-jude-bellingham-position-at-real-madrid |archive-date=9 May 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://en.as.com/soccer/jude-bellingham-was-a-no-9-and-didnt-know-it-n/ |title=Jude Bellingham was a 9 and didn't know it |last1=Tavero |first1=Fernando S. |last2=Quaile |first2=Kieran |website=Diario AS |date=26 August 2023 |access-date=17 April 2024 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240417201512/https://en.as.com/soccer/jude-bellingham-was-a-no-9-and-didnt-know-it-n/ |archive-date=17 April 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> This change in position led to Bellingham adopting a more significant role in the final third and scoring goals: 10 in his first 10 matches for Madrid.<ref name="10 in 10 all comps" /><ref name="BBC 14 in 15" />

His skill as a young player has enabled him to win several awards, including the [[IFFHS#The World's Best Youth (U20) Player|IFFHS World's Best Youth (U20) Player]] in 2022 and 2023,<ref name="IFFHS U20 2022" /><ref name="IFFHS U20 2023" /> and the [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy award]] and [[Kopa Trophy]] in 2023.<ref name="2023 GoldenBoy" /><ref name="2023Kopa" /> [[ESPN]] rated Bellingham as the number one central midfielder for 2022–23,<ref name="ESPN FC100 2223" /> and ''[[90min]]'' rated him as the top central midfielder in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/the-25-best-central-midfielders-in-world-football-ranked |title=The 25 best central midfielders in world football – ranked |website=90min |date=13 November 2022 |access-date=27 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240221094240/https://www.90min.com/posts/the-25-best-central-midfielders-in-world-football-ranked |archive-date=21 February 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Outside football==
[[File:Jude Bellingham during an EA Sports event in September 2024 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Bellingham during the ''[[EA Sports FC 25]]'' launch event in September 2024]]

In May 2024, Bellingham signed a multi-year deal with sports drink [[Lucozade]] becoming the face of the brand's multi-million pound TV campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bellingham Lands Lucozade Endorsement Deal|url=https://www.sportindustry.biz/news-categories/news/jude-bellingham-lucozade-deal-ambassador-england-euro-2024-real-madrid/|work=Sport Industry Group|date=15 May 2024|access-date=5 March 2025|archive-date=23 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240523204054/https://www.sportindustry.biz/news-categories/news/jude-bellingham-lucozade-deal-ambassador-england-euro-2024-real-madrid/|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2024, he appeared in [[Kim Kardashian]]'s shapewear and clothing brand [[Skims]]' campaign; the photoshoot featured Bellingham modelling men's underwear.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid Star Jude Bellingham Is the Newest Face of Kim Kardashian's SKIMS — See Photos|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/jude-bellingham-skims-campaign|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=12 June 2024|access-date=26 July 2024|archive-date=27 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240727001459/https://www.teenvogue.com/story/jude-bellingham-skims-campaign|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2024, Bellingham was revealed as the cover star for the video game ''[[EA Sports FC 25]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Jude Bellingham Revealed as EA SPORTS FC™ 25 Cover Star|url= https://news.ea.com/press-releases/press-releases-details/2024/Jude-Bellingham-Revealed-as-EA-SPORTS-FC-25-Cover-Star/default.aspx |work=news.ea.com |date= 2024|access-date=12 December 2024}}</ref> In the same month, [[Adidas]] launched Bellingham's first-ever signature collection, featuring a jersey, tracksuit, ringer tee, and shorts, all adorned with the JB monogram logo.<ref>{{cite web|title=adidas Unveil Jude Bellingham's First-Ever Signature Line|url=https://www.versus.uk.com/articles/adidas-unveil-jude-bellinghams-new-signature-line|work=Versus|date=26 July 2024|access-date=26 July 2024|archive-date=27 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240727001840/https://www.versus.uk.com/articles/adidas-unveil-jude-bellinghams-new-signature-line|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2024, [[Louis Vuitton]] named him as a "Friend of the House," announcing their partnership.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jude Bellingham signs lucrative Louis Vuitton deal to follow in David Beckham's footsteps|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/jude-bellingham-louis-vuitton-beckham-33482272.amp|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=16 August 2024|access-date=19 August 2024|archive-date=9 October 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241009133023/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/jude-bellingham-louis-vuitton-beckham-33482272.amp|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2024. Bellingham started his official channel on [[YouTube]] with a behind-the-scenes documentary of his first year in Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title= Coming for Cristiano Ronaldo? Jude Bellingham launches new YouTube channel as Real Madrid & England star reveals trailer for behind-the-scenes documentary of first year in Spain|url= https://www.goal.com/en/lists/cristiano-ronaldo-jude-bellingham-youtube-channel-real-madrid-england-star-documentary/blt5607eac422843d34|work=Goal.com|date=5 September 2024|access-date=10 September 2024}}</ref> In December 2024, he appeared in Adidas' documentary film ''Under the Tongue''.<ref>{{cite web|title= What To Expect From Our 'Under The Tongue' adidas Predator Documentary|url= https://www.soccerbible.com/news/2024/12/what-to-expect-from-our-under-the-tongue-adidas-predator-documentary/ |work= SoccerBible |date=9 December 2024|access-date=12 December 2024}}</ref>

In July 2025, he was revealed as one of the cover stars for ''[[EA Sports FC 26]]'' along with [[Jamal Musiala]] and [[Zlatan Ibrahimović]] for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13397511/ea-fc-26-jude-bellingham-jamal-musiala-zlatan-ibrahimovic-revealed-as-cover-stars-for-new-game|title= EA FC 26: Jude Bellingham, Jamal Musiala, Zlatan Ibrahimovic revealed as cover stars for new game|work= Sky Sports|date=17 July 2025|access-date=21 July 2025}}</ref> In September 2025, he was announced as [[Laureus World Sports Awards|Laureus]] ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.laureus.com/news/jude-bellingham-announced-as-laureus-ambassador|title= Jude Bellingham announced as Laureus Ambassador|work= Laureus|date=25 September 2025|access-date=10 October 2025}}</ref> In November 2025, Bellingham launched his own app, "JB5".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/reel/DRPfoo8DC94/?igsh=OXhvbDJ2NjZvNWx2|title=Jude Bellingham post on Instagram |work= Instagram|date=19 November 2025|access-date=20 November 2025}}</ref> In April 2026, he bought minority stake in [[Birmingham Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/jude-bellingham-birmingham-phoenix-stake-hundred/article70891808.ece/amp/|title= Jude Bellingham buys stake in Birmingham Phoenix: Real Madrid star enters cricket |work= Sportstar|date=22 April 2026|access-date=22 April 2026}}</ref>

